\- references read as ideas, not page numbers.
   define a schema once, name your sources, build an argument map. -\

\- 1. define the citation schema -\

#cite: ||author, title, year, publisher, page|| ! ::author:: (::year::, p. ::page::). _::title::_. ::publisher::. !

\- 2. define your sources as named instances of it -\

#weil:   ! Simone Weil, Gravity and Grace, 1952, Routledge, !
#berger: ! John Berger, Ways of Seeing, 1972, Penguin, !

\- 3. argument map — name the idea, not the page -\

#weil_attention:  @weil! p. 42 !
#weil_generosity: @weil! p. 117 !
#berger_looking:  @berger! p. 9 !

\- 4. write prose. citations are two words long and name ideas. -\

Attention, as @weil_attention argued, is the rarest form of generosity.
Berger complicates this @berger_looking by insisting that we never look
at one thing alone.

\- when a reference needs no parameters at all, the bare name is enough -\

The lamp burned, as @weil knew it would.
